[2.10] Price elasticities of steaks

data1 = read.csv("~/Personal Drive/Northwestern University/Fall 2023/MLDS 401 - TA/Labs/steakprices.csv") %>%
  mutate_at(vars(Chuck.Price, PortHse.Price, RibEye.Price), ~as.numeric(gsub("\\$", "", .)))

The power law \(y = ax^b\) is used to model the demand-price relationship in economies, and \(b\) represents the price elasticity of the demand for the product. Following are plots for \(\log{Q}\) versus \(\log{P}\) of all three steaks.

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(log(data1$Chuck.Price), log(data1$Chuck.Qty), xlab = "log(Price)", ylab = "log(Quantity)", main = "Chuck")
plot(log(data1$`PortHse.Price`), log(data1$`PortHse.Qty`), xlab = "log(Price)", ylab = "log(Quantity)", main = "Porterhouse")
plot(log(data1$`RibEye.Price`), log(data1$`RibEye.Qty`), xlab = "log(Price)", ylab = "log(Quantity)", main = "Rib Eye")

According to the above scatter plots, for all three types of steaks, the data follow a (negative) linear relationship between \(\log{Q}\) and \(\log{P}\). Thus, we fitted the model: \[\ln{Q} = \ln{a} + b\ln{P}\]

a)

fit_chuck = lm(log(Chuck.Qty) ~ log(Chuck.Price), data = data1)
fit_ph = lm(log(PortHse.Qty) ~ log(PortHse.Price), data = data1)
fit_rib = lm(log(RibEye.Qty) ~ log(RibEye.Price), data = data1)

To estimate the price elasticity is to estimate \(b\). Results are summarized as following:

Steaks Price Elasticity Estimates P-values
Chuck -1.3687 9.44e-05 ***
Porterhouse -2.6565 1.23e-12 ***
Rib Eye -1.446 0.000335 ***

All three coefficients are negative, indicating that demand drops as price increases. The negative price effect is most pronounced for porter house steak (most expensive) and least pronounced for chuck steak (least expensive).



b)

If the price is increased by 10% then chuck demand will drop by 13.69%, the porter demand by 26.57% and the rib eye demand by 14.46%.




[2.11] Smoking vs. Cancer

a) Scatter Plots

data2 = read.csv("~/Personal Drive/Northwestern University/Fall 2023/MLDS 401 - TA/Labs/smoking-cancer.csv")
plot(data2[, -1])



b) Correlation Tests

testB = cor.test(x = data2$Smoke, y = data2$Bladder)
testL = cor.test(x = data2$Smoke, y = data2$Lung)
testK = cor.test(x = data2$Smoke, y = data2$Kidney)
testLK = cor.test(x = data2$Smoke, y = data2$Leukemia)

Performed tests on the correlations \(H_{0}: \rho = 0\). The significance level is \(\alpha = 0.05\) and 95% confidence intervals are computed. All the results were summarized as following:

Cancer r t statistic p-value 95% CI
Bladder 0.7036 6.4173 0 (0.5141, 0.8276)
Lung 0.6974 6.3064 0 (0.5051, 0.8237)
Kidney 0.4874 3.6174 8e-04 (0.2227, 0.6851)
Leukemia -0.0685 -0.4449 0.6587 (-0.3581, 0.2331)

From all four types of cancer, only Leukemia has p-value\(> 0.05\), and its 95% confidence interval includes 0, so Leukemia is not significantly correlated with cigarette smoking. Among other three cancers that are significantly correlated with smoking, Bladder has the smallest p-value, and greatest correlation coefficient in magnitude (the closest r to 1). Therefore, Bladder is the most significantly correlated with cigarette smoking.




Question 3

x = c(5.8, 8.8, 11.0, 13.6, 18.5, 21.0, 23.7, 26.0, 28.3, 31.9, 36.5, 38.2, 40.4)
y = c(7.8, 8.2, 6.9, 5.3, 4.7, 4.9, 4.3, 2.7, 2.8, 1.8, 1.9, 1.1, 0.4)

n = length(x)
xtotal = sum(x)
ytotal = sum(y)
Sxx = (n - 1) * var(x)
Sxy = (n - 1) * cov(x, y)
Syy = (n - 1) * var(y)
xbar = mean(x)
ybar = mean(y)

fit = lm(y ~ x)

a) Linear Equation

beta1 = Sxy/Sxx
beta0 = ybar - beta1 * xbar

\(\hat{\beta}_1 = \dfrac{S_{xy}}{S_{xx}} = -0.2157\) and \(\hat{\beta}_0 = \bar{y} - \hat{\beta}_1 \bar{x} = 9.101\). Then our line is \(\hat{y} = 9.101 - 0.2157 x\).

We can check the result from linear regression:

summary(fit)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = y ~ x)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -0.86726 -0.41025  0.01393  0.31147  0.99731

## Multiple R-squared:  0.9546, Adjusted R-squared:  0.9505 
## F-statistic: 231.5 on 1 and 11 DF,  p-value: 9.805e-09



b) Prediction for \(x = 25\)

x0 = 25
ypred1 = beta0 + beta1 * x0
predict(fit, newdata = data.frame(x = 25))
##        1 
## 3.708097

\[\hat{y} = 9.101 - 0.2157 \times 25 = 3.7081\].



c) Prediction for \(x = 45\)

x0 = 45
ypred2 = beta0 + beta1 * x0
predict(fit, newdata = data.frame(x = 45))
##          1 
## -0.6062183

\[\hat{y} = 9.101 - 0.2157 \times 45 = -0.6062\].

Our maximum \(x\) value in our sample is 40.4, so 45 is outside our calculation and because of that our solution is not trustworthy.



d) \(R^2\)

r = Sxy/sqrt(Sxx * Syy)
r2 = r^2

\[r = \frac{S_{xy}}{\sqrt{S_{xx}S_{yy}}} = \frac{-341.9592}{\sqrt{1,585.231 \times 77.2708}} = -0.9771\] and then \(R^{2} = r^2 = 0.9546\). We can explain 95% of the variation in the data with the known values of x.



e) 95% CI for \(\hat{\beta}_1\)

sigma2 = (1 - r2) * Syy/(n-2)
se_beta1 = sqrt(sigma2 / Sxx)
ci = beta1 + c(-1, 1) * qt(1 - 0.01/2, df = n - 2) * se_beta1
confint(fit)
##                  2.5 %     97.5 %
## (Intercept)  8.2946906  9.9072895
## x           -0.2469194 -0.1845121

From class, we know \[ r^2 = 1-\frac{\text{SSE}}{\text{SST}} \implies \text{SSE}= (1- r^2)\text{SST}= (1 - r^2)S_{yy}\] \[\sigma^2 = \text{MSE}= \frac{\text{SSE}}{n - 2} = \frac{(1 - r^2)S_{yy}}{n - 2} = 0.3186\] \[S_{\hat{\beta}_1} = \sqrt{\frac{\sigma^2}{S_{xx}}} = 0.0142\]

The 95% CI for \(\hat{\beta}_1\) is: \[\hat{\beta}_1 \pm t_{1 - \alpha/2, n-2} S_{\hat{\beta}_1} = -0.2157 \pm 3.1058 \times 0.0142 = [-0.2597, -0.1717]\]



f) 95% CI for \(\hat{y}\) at \(x = 25\)

x0 = 25
sigma = sqrt(sigma2)
se_ypred = sigma * sqrt(1/n + (x0 - xbar)^2/Sxx)
ci = ypred1 + c(-1, 1) * qt(1 - 0.05/2, df = n - 2) * se_ypred
predict(fit, newdata = data.frame(x = 25), interval = "confidence")
##        fit      lwr     upr
## 1 3.708097 3.359753 4.05644

\[S_{\hat{y}|x_0} = \sigma\sqrt{\frac{1}{n} + \frac{(\bar{x}- x_0)^2}{S_{xx}}} = 0.1583\]

The 95% CI for the predicted value is: \[\hat{y}\pm t_{1 - \alpha/2, n-2} S_{\hat{y}|x_0} = `y_pred1` \pm 2.201 \times 0.1583 = [3.3598, 4.0564]\].



g) 95% PI for \(\hat{y}\) at \(x = 25\)

x0 = 25
se_ypred2 = sigma * sqrt(1 + 1/n + (x0 - xbar)^2/Sxx)
ci = ypred1 + c(-1, 1) * qt(1 - 0.05/2, df = n - 2) * se_ypred2
predict(fit, newdata = data.frame(x = 25), interval = "prediction")
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 3.708097 2.417814 4.998379

\[S_{Y|x_0} = \sigma\sqrt{1 + \frac{1}{n} + \frac{(\bar{x}- x_0)^2}{S_{xx}}} = 0.5862\]

The 95% PI for the predicted value is: \[\hat{y}\pm t_{1 - \alpha/2, n-2} S_{y|x_0} = `y_pred1` \pm 2.201 \times 0.5862 = [2.4178, 4.9984]\].
